Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/populationSize
Object: The size of a population, for example: an electorate or constituency group.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/
Object: A model describing incumbencies resulting from general elections, by-elections for seats in the House of Commons, by-elections for excepted hereditary peers in the House of Lords and elections for positions including that of the Speaker of the House of Commons. The model describes the result of an election regardless of the process by which that election has been conducted, and covers election returns by the 'first past the post' system and those which follow other methods. Where applicable, the model is aligned with the Cabinet Office Election Result Data Standard.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/Candidacy
Object: A candidacy of a person standing in an election, for example: Phillip Hammond standing as the Conservative Party candidate in Runnymede and Weybridge, at the 2015 General Election.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/adjunctTo
Object: Relates an adjunct certification to a certification, for example: relating a Co-operative Party certification to a Labour Party certification.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/hasPoliticalParty
Object: Relates a candidacy to a political party.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/resultPosition
Object: The relative position of the result of the candidacy in an election.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/candidateName
Object: The name of the candidate as it appears on the ballot.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/hasCandidacyResult
Object: Relates a candidacy to the result of that candidacy in an election.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/ballotsSpoiled
Object: The number of spoiled ballots cast by an electorate in an election, for example: ballots on which votes are given for more candidates than the voter is entitled to vote for, ballots on which anything is written or marked by which the voter can be identified, or ballots which are unmarked or void for uncertainty.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/hasElectorate
Object: Relates a constituency group to a group of people who at the time of an election to the House of Commons are eligible to vote in the election for that constituency. Electorates in an election to the House of Commons are related to a constituency group; electorates for excepted hereditary peerage seats and for positions within Parliament are not.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/totalVotesCast
Object: The total number of votes cast across all candidacies in an election, including spoiled ballots. Turnout is defined by the House of Commons Library as the total number of votes cast and not spoiled, divided by the size of the electorate. This definition conforms to the generally accepted academic usage. Turnout is generally defined by Returning Officers as the total number of votes cast divided by the size of the electorate.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/GeneralElection
Object: A set of elections to seats in the House of Commons held in all constituencies concurrently.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/CandidacyResult
Object: The result of a candidacy in an election, for example: Phillip Hammond's win as the Conservative Party candidate in Runnymede and Weybridge, at the 2015 General Election.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/ConstituencyGroup
Object: A group of people represented by an election winner.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/inElection
Object: Relates a candidacy to the election that candidacy is in.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/voteCount
Object: The number of accepted votes recorded for a candidacy.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/Certification
Object: A certification of a candidate by a political party to stand in an election on behalf of that party. A candidate may be certified by more than one party, for example: by both The Labour Party and The Co-operative Party.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/Election
Object: An election to elect a candidate or candidates to a seat or position.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/declarationTime
Object: The date and time at which results were declared for an election, for example: the declaration of the results in a constituency election, by the Returning Officer.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/PoliticalParty
Object: An organisation registered with the Electoral Commission as a political party.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/round
Object: The number of the round in an election having more than one round of voting.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/WinningCandidacyResult
Object: Used to record the winning candidacy in an election.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/hasCandidate
Object: Relates a candidacy to a person being a candidate.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/recordedDate
Object: The date on which a population size was recorded.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/voteShare
Object: The share of a vote won in an election by a candidate as a fraction of the accepted votes.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/ParliamentPeriod
Object: The time period of a single Parliament between the date of its first assembly after a general election and its dissolution. A Parliament period contains contiguous session and prorogation periods. During a parliament period Parliament is either in session or prorogued. The start date of a Parliament may be changed by subsequent proclamations. A Parliament ends at the next dissolution. While the Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011 was in force, the date of dissolution was determined by that Act or was named in a proclamation following a vote in Parliament for an early general election. The next Parliament began on the date named in the proclamation issued following a dissolution. Before the Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011 came into force and after that Act was repealed by the Dissolution and Calling of Parliament Act 2022, the date of dissolution is fixed by proclamation. The dissolution proclamation also names the date for Parliament to reassemble. Parliament periods are the same across both Houses. Parliaments are numbered ordinally from the first Parliament of the United Kingdom, sitting in 1801.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/isPartOfGeneralElection
Object: Relates a constituency election held as part of a general election to that general election.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/eligibleToVoteIn
Object: Relates a group of people - who at the time of an election are eligible to vote in that election - to that election.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/Electorate
Object: A group of people who are eligible to vote in an election called at a particular time, for example: the group of people entitled to vote in a constituency election, or members of the House of Commons voting for their Speaker.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/ConstituencyArea
Object: An area within which members of a constituency group reside. Constituency areas bounding constituency groups represented in the House of Commons are set out by the Boundary Commissions and approved by Parliament.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/toPoliticalParty
Object: Relates a certification of a candidate to the party issuing the certification.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/hasCertification
Object: Relates a candidacy to a certification of the candidate by a political party.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/intoParliamentPeriod
Object: Relates an election to the House of Commons to the Parliament period within which any resulting incumbency takes place.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/boundedBy
Object: Relates a constituency group to a geographic area. Constituency groups represented in the House of Commons are within a constituency area. Some historical constituency groups had no defined geographical extent, for example: Oxford University. A boundary set change will result in the creation of both a new constituency area and a new constituency group.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/election/partyGained
Object: Whether the party certification of the winning candidate at an election differs from the party certification of the winning candidate at the preceding election.
